data.value: Anterior to Area 6 is the frontal field of the eye (Area 8), which controls voluntary eye movements, as well as the conjugated eye movements. • The secondary motor area corresponds to the secondary somesthesiatic area (fields 40 and 43) over which they overlap. It plays a role in ipsilateral motor control of the face. • The additional motor area is located on the medial face of the upper frontal girder, anterior to the primary area. Its stimulation results in three types of movements: Posture adaptation, complex stereotypical movements, and rapid uncoordinated movements. • Extrapyramidal areas occupy almost all of the cortex region, but especially the premotor area 6, the additional motor area (medial face of the upper frontal girder) and the secondary motor area. The area occupied by extrapyramidal areas accounts for 85% of the total motor cortex. These areas include the subpressive areas, the origin of parapyramidal fibers and the extrapyramidal areas themselves. • The subpressive areas, whose stimulation inhibits the functioning of the primary motor area, are: 45, 6s precentral, 25 postcentral, 19, occipital and 24 cingular. The subpressor influx of these areas reaches the caudate nucleus, which transmits it to globus pallidus. It transmits it, via the thalamus, to the precentral crust of fields 4 and 6. In this cortico-strio-palidothalamic-cortical circuit, the thalamus acts as a centralizer, controlling the amplitude and how the movement was executed. • The extrapyramidal areas themselves are assigned to the fronto-parito-temporal cortex and less occipital. The main character of these areas is the reduced excitability from that of field 4, which manifests itself controllabally. From these extrapyramidal areas, corticopontine fibers leave which reach the nuclei in the bridge and from here, through pontocerebellar fibers, to the bark of the cerebellum (neocerebellum). From the bark of the cerebellum, they reach the toothed nucleus, then the thalamus, and from here back to the cerebral crust, closing the cortico-ponto-cerebelo-thalamo-cortical circuit. The role of this circuit is to bring the nervous influx of cerebellar Regulation into the execution of voluntary movements. • Vegetative areas are found in the cingulate gir, in the orbital ridgings of the frontal lobe, in the hippocampus and in the lob of the island. This ensemble forms the visceral brain. It is connected in both directions to the thalamus, hypothalamus and limbic system.

The primary auditory area is located on the upper face of the upper temporal giro in the Heschll transverse gires, fields 41 and partially 42, which receive geniculo-temporal inputs from the medial geniculate body. The secondary hearing area consists of field 42 (partial) and field 22. The excitation of fields 42 and 22 produces the sensation of whistling, bell-banging or cricer-creeping. Damage to field 22 causes sensory aphasia (the patient hears, but cannot interpret the sound, especially words). • The gustatory area is located immediately above the lateral moat Sylvius, in the lower region of the postcentral giro, field 43. • The vestibular area has no precise location; according to some authors it would be located in the upper temporal gir, behind the auditory artery, after others it would be located in the parietal lobe. • The olfactory area is located in the piriform cortex, the entorinal area, field 28. The destruction, experimentally in animals and accidentally in humans, of these related projection areas leads to loss of sensitivity in the case of the sensitive area, or to loss of function in the case of sensory areas (blindness, deafness, central type anosmia, although the respective recipient organs are intact). • The efferent projection areas are the origin of the cortico-fugitive pathways.

data.value: Cortical areas, by their function, can be classified into: Related projection areas, receivers or sensory, efferent, motor or motor protection areas and association areas. In reality, all sensory or motor projection areas receive input and send efferences, so the correct name would be sensory-motor areas, particularly for pre- and post-central areas. The related projection areas are: Somesthetic, visual, auditory, gustatory, olfactory and vestibular. • The primary area of general sensitivity (primary somesthesiatic area) is located in the left central gir, fields 3, 1, 2. In the primary area, the centers are located from top to bottom, behind the inverted figure of the body. The body is presented in the form of a monstrous caricature, in which the lips, tongue and hand stand out with the fingers, especially the polices. This inverted projection of the body was called the sensitive homunculus.
